{"actual_usd":0.1601,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":286,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31162,"reply":"\"Yeah, that’s exactly the pressure point, isn’t it?\" *I push my glasses up and glance off toward the bright edge of the square, buying half a beat to answer it cleanly.* \"If he’s only an example, then the cross starts looking wasteful. Tragic, maybe moving, but not necessary.\"\n\n\"I don’t think Christianity lets you stop there.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"A good example can show me what love is. It can’t reconcile me to God. It can’t bear sin just by being admirable. If Jesus only lived beautifully, then I’m still left with the same actual problem: I need more than instruction. I need rescue.\"\n\n\"The cross matters because Christianity is making a bigger claim than ‘here is the ideal man.’ It’s saying God dealt with something real there—sin, guilt, judgment, estrangement. Not just gave us a picture.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"Otherwise the apostles are talking way too strongly. They don’t talk like, ‘he inspired us wonderfully.’ They talk like something happened.\"\n\n\"And honestly—\" *I tap a thumb once against the bench slat beside me.* \"—if all I needed was a moral example, I was already condemned by the good ones I’ve got. The problem isn’t that I’ve never seen love. It’s that I don’t keep it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":58.64338000000002,"run_id":"5a2d2044-3fc3-456a-87a6-2d6c1a99b394"}
